    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "The code\r\n```cython\r\nfrom time import time\r\n\r\ndef show_the_trick():\r\n    z = 0\r\n    cdef float x = time()\r\n    y = time()\r\n    z = x\r\n    print(\"y = {}, z = {}\".format(y, z))\r\n```\r\ngives very strange result:\r\n```sh\r\n>>> show_the_trick()\r\ny = 1522347701.6019838, z = 1522347648.0\r\n>>> show_the_trick()\r\ny = 1522347702.2980115, z = 1522347648.0\r\n>>> show_the_trick()\r\ny = 1522347702.9860392, z = 1522347648.0\r\n>>> show_the_trick()\r\ny = 1522347703.6420138, z = 1522347648.0\r\n>>> show_the_trick()\r\ny = 1522347704.2820802, z = 1522347648.0\r\n>>> show_the_trick()\r\ny = 1522347705.6421106, z = 1522347648.0\r\n>>> show_the_trick()\r\ny = 1522347753.8016214, z = 1522347776.0\r\n>>> \r\n```\r\nso, if assignment from cython variable to python variable is incorrect, it would be nice to say it at Cythonizing stage. Versions tested were \r\ncython - 0.26.1 (can't find a deb for 0.28.xx and too lazy to compile)\r\npython - 3.5 and 3.6 versions",
    "closed_at": "2018-03-29T19:50:02Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "The issue here is that the line `cdef float x = time()` explicitly assigns the result of time() to a lower-precision C type `float`. For most applications, there's little if any reason to uses single-precision floats these days, especially for something like timestamps (which only allow for multi-minute granularity). Better to just use `double`s everywhere. \r\n\r\n",
